        "body":  "# Semiconductor Module Study Document\n\n## Module Goal\n\nBuild a closed learning loop for Semiconductor: concepts, formulas, engineering applications, and verifiable artifacts. This module covers: Band theory, Doping, PN junction, MOSFET, CMOS, Short-channel effects.\n\n## Recommended Resource\n\n[MIT 6.012 Microelectronic Devices](https://ocw.mit.edu/courses/6-012-microelectronic-devices-and-circuits-fall-2009/)\n\n## Foundational Source\n\n[Shockley, 1949, The Theory of p-n Junctions](https://doi.org/10.1002/j.1538-7305.1949.tb03645.x)\n\n## Core Formula / Model\n\nMOS current approximation: `I_D ~= 1/2*mu*Cox*(W/L)*(V_GS-V_TH)^2`. Gate voltage controls channel current.\n\nHow to study the formula:\n\n- Identify every variable and decide whether it is physical, geometric, statistical, or computational.\n- Write the assumptions that make the formula valid.\n- Verify one minimal example using numbers, a plot, or code.\n\n## Daily Prompt Template\n\n| Field | Content |\n|---|---|\n| Theory Name | Today\u0027s theory or model name |\n| Real-world Problem | What real engineering problem it solves |\n| Core Equation | The central equation or invariant |\n| Derivation Starting Point | Which definition, conservation law, or assumption starts the derivation |\n| Physical/Geometric Meaning | Physical, geometric, or system-level meaning |\n| Failure Conditions | When the model breaks |\n| Cross-domain Connections | Links to other modules |\n| Engineering Applications | Practical engineering use cases |\n| Simulation / Verification | How you verified it today |\n| What I Truly Understood Today | The one thing you genuinely understood |\n\n## Module Daily Index\n\n| Day | Topic | Key Question | Practice |\n|---:|---|---|---|\n| Day 91 | Band theory | Why are materials conductive? | Band diagram sketch |\n| Day 92 | Doping | How do N/P semiconductors work? | Carrier simulations |\n| Day 93 | PN junction | Why do diodes conduct one-way? | Diode IV curves |\n| Day 94 | MOSFET | Why does voltage control current? | MOSFET transfer curves |\n| Day 95 | CMOS | Why is CMOS power-efficient? | CMOS inverter SPICE |\n| Day 96 | Short-channel effects | Why are advanced nodes hard? | Leakage analysis |\n| Day 116 | Band theory | Why are materials conductive? | Band diagram sketch |\n| Day 117 | Doping | How do N/P semiconductors work? | Carrier simulations |\n| Day 118 | PN junction | Why do diodes conduct one-way? | Diode IV curves |\n| Day 119 | MOSFET | Why does voltage control current? | MOSFET transfer curves |\n| Day 120 | CMOS | Why is CMOS power-efficient? | CMOS inverter SPICE |\n| Day 121 | Short-channel effects | Why are advanced nodes hard? | Leakage analysis |\n| Day 136 | Band theory | Why are materials conductive? | Band diagram sketch |\n| Day 137 | Doping | How do N/P semiconductors work? | Carrier simulations |\n| Day 138 | PN junction | Why do diodes conduct one-way? | Diode IV curves |\n| Day 139 | MOSFET | Why does voltage control current? | MOSFET transfer curves |\n| Day 140 | CMOS | Why is CMOS power-efficient? | CMOS inverter SPICE |\n| Day 141 | Short-channel effects | Why are advanced nodes hard? | Leakage analysis |\n| Day 156 | Band theory | Why are materials conductive? | Band diagram sketch |\n| Day 157 | Doping | How do N/P semiconductors work? | Carrier simulations |\n| Day 158 | PN junction | Why do diodes conduct one-way? | Diode IV curves |\n| Day 159 | MOSFET | Why does voltage control current? | MOSFET transfer curves |\n| Day 160 | CMOS | Why is CMOS power-efficient? | CMOS inverter SPICE |\n| Day 161 | Short-channel effects | Why are advanced nodes hard? | Leakage analysis |\n| Day 176 | Band theory | Why are materials conductive? | Band diagram sketch |\n| Day 177 | Doping | How do N/P semiconductors work? | Carrier simulations |\n| Day 178 | PN junction | Why do diodes conduct one-way? | Diode IV curves |\n| Day 179 | MOSFET | Why does voltage control current? | MOSFET transfer curves |\n| Day 180 | CMOS | Why is CMOS power-efficient? | CMOS inverter SPICE |\r\n"
