        "body":  "# Architecture Module Study Document\n\n## Module Goal\n\nBuild a closed learning loop for Architecture: concepts, formulas, engineering applications, and verifiable artifacts. This module covers: Boolean algebra, Logic gates, Sequential logic, FSM, Pipeline, Cache, ISA, GPU.\n\n## Recommended Resource\n\n[MIT 6.004 Computation Structures](https://ocw.mit.edu/courses/6-004-computation-structures-spring-2009/)\n\n## Foundational Source\n\n[von Neumann, 1945, First Draft of a Report on the EDVAC](https://archive.org/details/firstdraftofrepo00vonn)\n\n## Core Formula / Model\n\nPerformance equation: `CPU Time = Instruction Count * CPI * Clock Cycle Time`. Optimize only after locating the bottleneck.\n\nHow to study the formula:\n\n- Identify every variable and decide whether it is physical, geometric, statistical, or computational.\n- Write the assumptions that make the formula valid.\n- Verify one minimal example using numbers, a plot, or code.\n\n## Daily Prompt Template\n\n| Field | Content |\n|---|---|\n| Theory Name | Today\u0027s theory or model name |\n| Real-world Problem | What real engineering problem it solves |\n| Core Equation | The central equation or invariant |\n| Derivation Starting Point | Which definition, conservation law, or assumption starts the derivation |\n| Physical/Geometric Meaning | Physical, geometric, or system-level meaning |\n| Failure Conditions | When the model breaks |\n| Cross-domain Connections | Links to other modules |\n| Engineering Applications | Practical engineering use cases |\n| Simulation / Verification | How you verified it today |\n| What I Truly Understood Today | The one thing you genuinely understood |\n\n## Module Daily Index\n\n| Day | Topic | Key Question | Practice |\n|---:|---|---|---|\n| Day 97 | Boolean algebra | Why can logic be mathematical? | Logic simplification |\n| Day 98 | Logic gates | Why is NAND universal? | Build NAND circuits |\n| Day 99 | Sequential logic | Why do systems need clocks? | Build flip-flops |\n| Day 100 | FSM | How do state machines work? | Traffic-light FSM |\n| Day 101 | Pipeline | Why are CPUs pipelined? | Pipeline timing |\n| Day 102 | Cache | Why does memory hierarchy matter? | Cache hit simulation |\n| Day 103 | ISA | Why do instruction sets matter? | Simple assembly coding |\n| Day 104 | GPU | Why are GPUs good for AI? | CUDA vector add |\n| Day 122 | Boolean algebra | Why can logic be mathematical? | Logic simplification |\n| Day 123 | Logic gates | Why is NAND universal? | Build NAND circuits |\n| Day 124 | Sequential logic | Why do systems need clocks? | Build flip-flops |\n| Day 125 | FSM | How do state machines work? | Traffic-light FSM |\n| Day 126 | Pipeline | Why are CPUs pipelined? | Pipeline timing |\n| Day 127 | Cache | Why does memory hierarchy matter? | Cache hit simulation |\n| Day 128 | ISA | Why do instruction sets matter? | Simple assembly coding |\n| Day 129 | GPU | Why are GPUs good for AI? | CUDA vector add |\n| Day 142 | Boolean algebra | Why can logic be mathematical? | Logic simplification |\n| Day 143 | Logic gates | Why is NAND universal? | Build NAND circuits |\n| Day 144 | Sequential logic | Why do systems need clocks? | Build flip-flops |\n| Day 145 | FSM | How do state machines work? | Traffic-light FSM |\n| Day 146 | Pipeline | Why are CPUs pipelined? | Pipeline timing |\n| Day 147 | Cache | Why does memory hierarchy matter? | Cache hit simulation |\n| Day 148 | ISA | Why do instruction sets matter? | Simple assembly coding |\n| Day 149 | GPU | Why are GPUs good for AI? | CUDA vector add |\n| Day 162 | Boolean algebra | Why can logic be mathematical? | Logic simplification |\n| Day 163 | Logic gates | Why is NAND universal? | Build NAND circuits |\n| Day 164 | Sequential logic | Why do systems need clocks? | Build flip-flops |\n| Day 165 | FSM | How do state machines work? | Traffic-light FSM |\n| Day 166 | Pipeline | Why are CPUs pipelined? | Pipeline timing |\n| Day 167 | Cache | Why does memory hierarchy matter? | Cache hit simulation |\n| Day 168 | ISA | Why do instruction sets matter? | Simple assembly coding |\n| Day 169 | GPU | Why are GPUs good for AI? | CUDA vector add |\r\n"
